714778f-a.title: Manhattan: 89th Street (East) - East End Avenue
714778f-a.text:
B9th Street, north side, from East End to York Avenues. All of the buildings seen on this block belong to the House of The Good Shepherd which is a Roman Catholic home for women.
August 2, 1927.
P. L. Sperr.

714777f-a.title: Manhattan: 89th Street (East) - East End Avenue
714777f-a.text:
East 89th Street, north side, between East End (Ave. B) and York (Ave.A) Aves. Site formerly occupied by the House of Good Shepherd.
March 29, 1929.
P. L. Sperr.

714776f-b.title: Manhattan: 89th Street (East) - East End Avenue
714776f-b.text:
(1)  East 89th Street, north side, at the northern terminus of East End Ave. This area, north of Carl Schurs Park is being filled in. The frame building shown on piles, is a U.S. Vol. Life Saving Station, and
is located at the foot of East 90th Street.
March 29, 1937.
P. L. Sperr.

The sameg another angle.
